        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Liuius, medulla Romani ingenij, et neruus animi virilis: statim post Sallustium, ipsumq[ue] Ca[e]sarem, instructissimus ad 
                        conscribendam Romanam Historiam; maximè omnium seriam, atq[ue] solidam.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Sallust"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="medulla Romani ingenii" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Livy, the marrow of Roman ingenuity and the strength of the manly mind: he comes directly after Sallust and Caesar himself as the most 
                skilled for writing Roman history, sober and substantial to the highest degree of all.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Liuianarum fermè concionum, perinsignis qua[e]dam; et Imperatoria, et Senatoria Maiestas, atq[ue] dignitas. 
                        Multa[e] sententia[e], vtriq[ue] Militia[e] apta[e], et in suo foro exquisita[e]. Synopsis qua[e]dam collectarum à Perionio Concionum.
                        Digna in singulis generibus curiosa Analyse. Vt sunt pla[e]raq[ue] prudenter, arguteq[ue] elegantia.
                        Sed harum concionum nemo lautior censor, quàm Quinctilianus, aut magnificentior pra[e]co.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Joachim Perion"/>
                    <person name="Quintilian"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Of practically [all] Livy’s speeches a very remarkable one: it has both imperial and senatorial majesty and dignity. 
                Many maxims suitable for either kind of military service, and carefully investigated in his own court of law. 
                There is a kind of summary of the speeches collected by Perionius. Worth a careful analysis in each of its categories, as most are elegant 
                in a judicious and bright way. But noone is a finer critic of these or a more distinguished announcer than Quintilian.           
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        {Ciceronis similior Ca[e]sar: Sallustij Liuius: Liuij Quinctilianus: Omnium Velleius. Tacitus esse maluit suus: Seneca esse uoluit
                        suissimus. Poetarum nemo delectu uerboru[m], phrasium, sententiarumq[ue] affinior Ciceroni, Ca[e]sari, et Terentio, quàm Virgilius. 
                        Vt ferè non magis poeta videatur, quàm Orator, aut historicus. Tam est exquisitè elegans, et prudens.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Sallust"/>
                    <person name="Quintilian"/>
                    <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
                    <person name="Tacitus"/>
                    <person name="Seneca"/>
                    <person name="Marcus Terentius Varro"/>
                    <person name="Virgil"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Caesar is more similar to Cicero, Livy to Sallust; Quintilian to Livy, Velleius Paterculus to all. Tacitus preferred to be his own man, 
                Seneca wanted to be himself in the highest degree. Of the poets noone is more akin to Cicero, Caesar and Terentius in choice of words, 
                diction and observations than Virgil. So that he practically seems less to be a poet than an orator or historian. So meticulously elegant 
                and prudent he is.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Inuectiua, i[nfr]a.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Attack, [see] above.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Qui vult Liuium penitùs percipere, diligenter legat Pontani Actium, de historia dialogum. Nec vnq[uam] obliuiscatur, Quinctilianum 
                        ca[e]teris Romanoru[m] historicis pra[e]tulisse Liuium, ac Sallustium: alterumq[ue] Herodoto, alteru[m] Thucydidi composuisse, qui in 
                        dicendo fuêre mirabiles. Scitè Seruilius Nouianus: 
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                <person name="Giovanni Pontano"/>
                <person name="Quintilian"/>
                <person name="Sallust"/>
                <person name="Herodotus"/>
                <person name="Thucydides"/>
                <person name="Servilius Novianus"/> 
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>pares eos esse magis, quàm similes. Sit Cicero elegantior paulò, aut concinnior: 
                        at penetrantior est Liuius, saepè pressior, pla[e]runq[ue] neruosior, et non rarò aliquid promit magis reconditum. Da saltem Ciceronis 
                        phrasin: Liuij emphasin.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                    <book title="Actius"/> 
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Who wants to understand Livy completely, should carefully read Actius, a dialogue about history by Pontanus. And he should never forget that 
                Quintilian preferred Livy and Sallust to the other historians of the Romans, and equated the one to Herodotos and the other to Thucydides, 
                who were wonderful in making speeches. Servilius Novianus [wrote] adroitly that they are equal rather than similar. Cicero may be a bit more 
                elegant or clever, but Livy is more thorough and often more concise, and generally more powerful, and not seldom brings forth something more 
                concealed. Anyhow, give [me] Cicero’s diction and Livy’s rhetorical stress.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Tolle conciones: restabunt fragmenta: ait ille.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Remove the speeches: they will remain fragments, he says.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        {Oratori, pragmatico, legato, regio consiliario, aulico deniq[ue] aut vrbano politico, multi hic eximij, et conspicui Iconismi. 
                        Nullius ferè emphasis, in quouis causaru[m] genere neruosior, aut efficatior.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Here for the orator, pragmatic ambassador, royal counsellor, finally the courtly or urban politician many outstanding and striking portrayals.
                Nobody’s rhetorical stress in whatever kind of subject is more powerful or effective.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
